One of the restrictive general propositions expressed from time to time for the purpose of informing an assessment of the proper scope of interrogatories (and also of subpoenas: see 
[33.4.20]
) is that “fishing” is impermissible. This expression, given OwenÂ J’s explanation of it in Associated Dominions Assurance Society Pty Ltd v John Fairfax & Sons Pty Ltd (1952) 72 WN (NSW) 250 atÂ 254Â , perhaps should be abandoned and the expression “(wide) netting” substituted — because it better captures the intended pejorative element. The essential element of the impermissible concept of “fishing” is that of using a wide net (ie, insufficient particularity, discrimination or direct relevance to the pleaded issues) cast to trawl for information that, if it exists, may assist the party interrogating to make out some case, and not necessarily the currently pleaded case. Interrogatories of these kinds are neither relevant nor necessary and are not permissible: Associated Dominions Assurance Society Pty Ltd v John Fairfax & Sons Pty Ltd (1952) 72 WN (NSW) 250 at 254Â  (OwenÂ J); see also WA Pines Pty Ltd v Bannerman (1980) 41 FLR 169; (1980) ATPR Â¶40-144Â ; Mulley & Marney v Manifold (1959) 103 CLR 341 atÂ 345; 33 ALJR 168;  BC5900640Â ; Blair v Queanbeyan City Council (1995) 88 LGERA 247;  BC9505590Â ].
